<p id="comment-truncated-5249-1195449367" class="comment">
To quote Bob Dylan, from his song, &quot;Like a Rolling Stone,&quot; 'When you ain't got nuthin', you got nuthin' to lose/ You're invisible now, you got no secrets to conceal.' Which can make a formerly nice enough girl become dangerous, willing to unzip it,...
</p>
<p id="comment-full-5249-1195449367" class="comment" style="display: none">
To quote Bob Dylan, from his song, &quot;Like a Rolling Stone,&quot; 'When you ain't got nuthin', you got nuthin' to lose/ You're invisible now, you got no secrets to conceal.' Which can make a formerly nice enough girl become dangerous, willing to unzip it, become a Truthteller. In art school one of the first things our teachers told us about the artworld was, no matter what happens, suck it up and swallow it, or you will be blacklisted. Interesting that was the expression I heard from men (for the most part) who had survived the repressive miasma of fifties McCarthyistic witch hunts. Witness the background color on this website: Fifties Green it was called. Shudder. But it's appropo to the decade I was born in, so I like it for my art. One of the first times I can remember being beyond embarrassment (danger!), willing to embarrass onother in public (danger! danger!) was in a crowded hallway of art revelers outside the Wirtz Gallery at 49 Geary in San Francisco, waiting to get on a crowded elevator. Just as the door opened, I caught sight of Jeff Nathanson in the far corner of the elevator. As we squeezed into the elevator I greeted him loudly, as though he were an old friend, I called him by name, said how glad I was to see him. A simple act on my part, yet I saw him blanche white, then burn red, as all eyes were upon him. What, you may wonder, prompted such an aggressive act on my part? Well, have a seat and I shall tell. Jeff Nathanson directed the Richmond Art Center, when I was approached by the Curator, Candice Farlice to make an Installation for the upcomming 500 year aniversary of the discovery of America by Christopher Columbus, and ensuing colonialization, along with the havoc, chaos, devastation and ruin wreaked on the people and nature of the Americas. Various artists and artist groups were invited to create for the show which would be exhibited the following year, titled: History, Truth or Consequences. Sure, I told Candice, right up my alley. The exhibition would showcase various atrocities throughout history relating to colonialization. When I told Candice I wished to install on the subject of the Holocaust, as my people are Jewish, I was informed the Holocaust was covered by another artist, Lisa Kokin. As I recently had been studying the witch-burnings of the Inquisition, and my people are women, ( The Spanish took the ball of the siezing of property, the imprisonment, the torture, and various methods of murdering, most noticably burning at the stake happening all over Europe, and ran with it.) Effecting many more women accused of witch-craft, though &quot;heretics&quot; of all kinds  were targeted, the atrocities lasted well over 300 years, eventually ended here in th U.S., back in Salem, MA. I suggested that as subject, and the idea met with approval from the Curator. Woo-hooo! I was on my way. Over the course of the next year drawings, plans, and sculptures in progress were examined and approved by the Curator, who presumably was consulting with the Director, each step of the way. After this year of planning, researching, and writing (for the wall text), all work was trucked from my studio in East Oakland to The Richmond Art Center. I installed diligently for two days, with a plan to document on the third day, the day before the Opening. The artwork which consisted of seven sculptures, several black painted industrial structures, a few large bags of potting soil, and about one-thousand burnt wooden matches, went up, like a lifeboat rising up out of a shipwrecked ocean. Candace loved my work, she had given me the prized center of the huge exhibition space. Everything was contained in a crystallization of the moment in history combined with my own torment as a child, a woman, an artist, a person in this world. I was thrilled. Candace was thrilled. I returned home in triumph to relax after the hurculean effort it took to pull it off. At home that evening, the phone rang. It was Candace. Jeff The Director didn't like it, didn't want it, wanted it dismantled. She sounded horrified and embarrassed. She, who was also being overridden, couldn't explain it, she mumbled awkwardly about it &quot;being too powerful for him.&quot; Two women burnt by a man, all these centuries later, the honor and homage I tried to do the suffering women of so long ago, bled through the centuries. Through the nauseated knowlege there was nothing to be done, I said I would be there as planned to photogragh the work done, then we could discuss how to re-present the work in a way that might satisfy the Little Lord Inquisitor. She agreed. I did not hear from her the next morning. Luckily a friend brought me there, was there to catch my crashing spirit on arrival to realize  the entire thing had been dismantled before I could document. Three sculptures were neatly placed on white pedestals, a tiny bit of soil sprinkled evenly on each; all sanitized, watered down to the satisfaction of Jeff Nathanson the Director. Candace the Curator was there and I doubt I will ever encounter a face so chagrined as hers was, when she greeted Chandra the Artist. I feel I let the Curator off easy, I think, when I encountered him at the elevator at 49 Geary, several weeks later.     
</p>
