<div class="one-comment gcBorder2">
<h3>
Chandra Garsson/ Purim (About Face)
</h3>
<span class="showFull">
| <a id="comment-more-toggle-5248-2018241106"
onclick="document.getElementById('comment-truncated-5248-2018241106').style.display='none';
document.getElementById('comment-full-5248-2018241106').style.display='block';
document.getElementById('comment-more-toggle-5248-2018241106').style.display='none';
document.getElementById('comment-less-toggle-5248-2018241106').style.display='inline'; return false;"
href="main.php?g2_view=core%253AShowItem&amp;g2_itemId=5245&amp;g2_imageViewsIndex=1">show full</a><a id="comment-less-toggle-5248-2018241106"
onclick="document.getElementById('comment-truncated-5248-2018241106').style.display='block';
document.getElementById('comment-full-5248-2018241106').style.display='none';
document.getElementById('comment-more-toggle-5248-2018241106').style.display='inline';
document.getElementById('comment-less-toggle-5248-2018241106').style.display='none'; return false;"
href="main.php?g2_view=core%253AShowItem&amp;g2_itemId=5245&amp;g2_imageViewsIndex=1" style="display: none">show summary</a>
</span>
<p id="comment-truncated-5248-2018241106" class="comment">
In 1991 I was invited by a curator at the Jewish Museum in San Francisco, name unremembered to hang work in 'Mask Invitational.' A very nice experience it was, I told the museum of several multi-culti friends who likewise did work that would fit in,...
</p>
<p id="comment-full-5248-2018241106" class="comment" style="display: none">
In 1991 I was invited by a curator at the Jewish Museum in San Francisco, name unremembered to hang work in 'Mask Invitational.' A very nice experience it was, I told the museum of several multi-culti friends who likewise did work that would fit in, they too were invited, a celebration of Purim, good food, a good time was had by all. Two years later, 1993, a new curator (name unremembered) invited me, and some of the old friends, including my Vietnamese boyfriend at the time, included both years, to all join in the multi-culti Purim festivities again at the museum. The show this time was called 'About Face', ironically enough. We all brought our work over to be installed, mine was in a prominently appropriate placement in the exhibit. Two to three nights before the opening I recieved a phone call from the curator. Well, she told me, best to come pick up your work before the opening (two pieces), it shan't be included after all. Not even a mumbled word of explanation, this time. I will admit my heart was broken. I told all my friends who had been included (most of them on my recomendation) and met with somewhat sympathetic silence. My boyfriend to his everlasting credit, got on the phone immediately the very next day, to tell the museum that unless they showed my work as promised, he would be removing his work from the exhibition as well. Daunted they were by this rare showing of solidarity. They relented. Trepidatious, I entered the night of the opening, boyfriend in his proud moment on my arm, entourage sheepishly trailing behind. my work was nowhere to be seen! I guzzled some champaigne, went in search, found it at last. My work had been relegated to the basement with the children's artwork, where the children were enjoying their own bemasked, becostumed Purim celebration, playing their child games. Well. Still young enough in those days to suck it up and swallow it, I philisophically and joyfully joined the children---with whom I have always gotten along very well---in thier games.
</p>
<p class="info">
